{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649198"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18351"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11069"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74338"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11069"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59829"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7472"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25676"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25679"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74338"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is part of the third layer of the plantar muscles of the foot?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Quadratus plantae","Plantar interossei","Flexor digitorum brevis","Abductor hallucis","Flexor hallucis brevis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe third layer of the plantar muscles of the foot consists of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor hallucis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E, adductor hallucis, and flexor digiti minimi brevis. These muscles are involved in the movement and stabilization of the toes, particularly the big toe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexor digitorum brevis\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the first layer of the plantar muscles, which also includes the abductor hallucis and abductor digiti minimi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuadratus plantae\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the second layer of the plantar muscles, along with the lumbricals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbductor hallucis\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the first layer of the plantar muscles, which also includes the flexor digitorum brevis and abductor digiti minimi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar interossei\u003C/strong\u003E are part of the fourth layer of the plantar muscles, which also includes the dorsal interossei.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The third layer of the plantar muscles of the foot includes the flexor hallucis brevis, adductor hallucis, and flexor digiti minimi brevis.","Understanding the anatomy of the foot is crucial for diagnosing and managing foot-related conditions."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"it